I put two screw holes on the supports for securing the plaque to a wooden surface if need be. Glue was used to attach the supports to the back of the holder.
Aluminum Plaques were custom cut and laser engraved by a seller on eBay. He makes them in different sizes and finishes.

This is to keep from accidentally flipping a toggle switch. In this case I intend to use it with a 1/2 hp 90V DC Permanent Magnet motor to control the rotation direction, if it is running and accidentally switched - bad things may happen to the motor or motor control (the magic smoke may get out of the wires).
This is for a toggle switch with a 12 mm stem and 16 mm nut (turned out to be 15 mm nut). In my case this is a NKK Toggle Switch S332T-RO.
There is clearance to put a deep well socket down over the switch stem to tighten the nut. The action of the switch would be aligned with the notches so it can be reached with finger tips. The 2 side holes near the bottom are for a pair of set screws to hold it from twisting on the shaft of the switch.
Print flat side down and clean up as needed.  The 2 side holes in the base are to be tapped for #6-32 set screws to keep it aligned with the toggle switch.

This is a two part FasTrak metro transponder holder that fits onto the circular shaft of my Toyota Matrix rear view mirror. I think this should be similar to Toyota Corolla's as well. Note that the fit around the rear view mirror shaft is tricky. The current design could be tightened up but be careful not to crack the clamp.

The holder for the transponder is designed to be snug with the velcro stickers on the back of the transponder. If your transponder does not have those, you will have to make it thinner or put something in there for a snug fit.

Also note the sketchup stl files are sometimes non-manifold so I usually fix it through netfabb and then print. The included STLs should have no problems.

70 3D printable lock pick templates. Use these templates to outline steel stock for creating your own lock picks.

This project started with a file I found on lockpicking101.com. While cutting out each template from paper was an option, I would much rather trace the outline. So I managed to convert the original template to a 3D file, and export in groups of about 15, all templates (5 files)

Original JPG was found here:

http://www.lockpicking101.com/viewtopic.php?f=4&t=17326&hilit=template&start-146

Credit for the original JPG goes to Lockpicking101.com user Alan5510301

Print at .1 layer height, 1 perimeter, no brim (we want to preserve the outline of the pick).
Once printed, you may want to spend 20 seconds or so cleaning up the edge of the template with a file so its sharp.
Lay it on you stock, outline with your choice of marker and get to grinding. I find the diamond bits seem to work the best.

Files:
70 All Picks.123dx is the original 123D Design file that contains all the picks, plus calibration squares.
70 Picks (1-5) STL files of picks
70 Pick Templates.Jpg - Original 2D templates

With a free download of 123D Design, you should be able to export individual picks as well as group only the picks you want to print into your own group from the 70 All Picks.123dx file.

DO NOT ATTEMPT TO PICK WITH THESE, THEY WILL BREAK OFF IN YOUR LOCK! (although if you do, let me know how it goes!)

comments.text:

description.text: This Connex Prosight antenna holder is designed to flex (made from TPU) while still keeping the pads fairly isolated from impact/twisting forces during crashes. The bridging "arch" allows the pads to be pulled away or pushed towards each other to absorb some of the impact, but prevents it from being done to the extent they could get damaged. The design has been crash tested many times, and did fairly well, but on one crash, the cable was ripped out of one of the pads, so it made me secure the cable and pads with hot glue, to prevent extra tension from ripping the cable, and the pads from popping out in extreme cases.

This customizer lets you create your own magnetic bases for openforge. Presently, I generally use this style with the tudor tiles, and the stone style for Cut-Stone tiles. Depending on the printer you are using, you may want to use this to increase or decrease the size of the holes so you get the proper fit.

Many people don't use the filament rivet option, so you may want to turn that off (set it to 0). If you want to use the base with an inch based system (such as DragonLock), you can generate imperial scaled bases now as well.

If you are using construction kit pieces, I suggest adding the construction kit supports, as they give a greater gluing area.

I started with an idea of a rubber band glider inspired by white wings and cheap balsa wood models. I sketched out the body of a normal Cessna 100 series looking body. Based on my experience and engineering knowledge I came up with some rough dimensions for the design, then started modeling in fusion 360.

Then I printed what I had and measured the center of gravity, then I started shaving material off the tail from my original design.
After a few revisions I printed one with wing roots, and some wings to test out. The design kept stalling.

I then revised the design to shave a lot more material off the tail.

Finally I was down to a design that would fly reasonably well with the wings I had.

The progression of body designs. Some were broken along the way (too thin).

I am a pilot. I have loved airplanes since I was old enough to talk. I have built hundreds of model planes, some fly some just look pretty. We need more young people interested in aerospace! So, I set out to design a project to make a practical exploration of wing design by making rubber band gliders with wings that can easily be replaced and tested with new designs. Objectives
  • Learn about aerodynamic forces - lift, drag, weight, thrust
  • Learn about flight
  • Learn about wing design.
    • Skills Learned (standards)
  • MP.4 - Model with mathematics. (HS-ETS1-1), (HS-ETS1-2), (HS-ETS1-3), (HS-ETS1-4)
  • RST.11-12.9 - Synthesize information from a range of sources (e.g., texts, experiments, simulations) into a coherent understanding of a process, phenomenon, or concept, resolving conflicting information when possible.
    • References
  • http://www.aeronautics.nasa.gov/pdf/wing_design_k-12.pdf
  • http://www.4p8.com/eric.brasseur/glider_physics.html

Lesson / Activity
Step 1 - Background Knowledge
  • Discuss aerodynamic forces
  • Discuss how wings work.
  • Discuss / show paper wing demonstration (paper taped together around a pencil and blow).
  • Discuss air resistance and friction.
  • Discuss center of gravity and how that relates to glider performance.
  • Discuss different styles of wings: rectangular, elliptical, swept (forward and rear), and delta
  • Print and use one or more of the gliders for visual aid.
  • Have students develop ideas on what wings are going to work better
    • Step 2 - Design and/or build
    Option 1:
  • Have students design a set of wings and print them.
  • The wing root has a 2.4mm square design ~18mm long, the wing will need an inside 3mm square ~20mm long to slip onto the root.
    • Option 2:
  • Print one or all the wings I have in the thing files.
    • Option 3:
  • As a class design a consensus set of wings and print it. (Maybe as an addon to Option 2.)
    • Option 4:
  • Let students modify or design their own body and wings.
    • Step 3 - Practical testing
    Option 1:
  • Assemble the glider. Left wing slipped onto the root & Right wing slipped onto the root.
    Photos below
    Left Wing -> Body <- Right Wing
    SAFETY NOTE: always be aware of what is down range
  • Setup range
  • Perform a repeatable scientific collection of data: Launch gliders with same angle, same direction, into same wind conditions.
  • Measure the distance to landing. (option to layout a landing grid ahead)
  • Record all data in a table of distances.
  • Repeat above for so each wing design launches the same number of times.
    • Option 2:
  • Do above with an iterative design process where students design a new set of wings and test those also.
    • Step 3 - Calculations
  • Have students evaluate their data for any trends and come up with the average distance their wing design was able to achieve.
  • Graph class wide data and determine which wing design, if any, was the best and why?
    • Step 4 - Review
  • Discuss why we got the results we got.
  • Discuss how students think they could do the experiment differently.
    • Rubric
  • What are the aerodynamic forces?
  • How does a wing work?
  • What is helping our design be more aerodynamic?
  • What is creating resistance for our designs?
  • How does friction (drag) apply to gliders?
  • What is center of gravity and how can the wings affect it?
    • Tips and Tricks
  • I spent many many revisions on the body trying to get a nice flight with a correct center of gravity
  • Weight of the wings matters GREATLY.
  • The wing root has a 2.4mm square design ~18mm long, the wing will need an inside 3mm square ~20mm long to slip onto the root.
  • Watch the video and note how I hold the rubber band and launch the glider. I had a group of elementary and middle school kids play with them and they tried everything, but kept coming back to me to learn my way to launch them
  • The glider can put a dent in your dry wall!

Accessories
The following materials and items can be helpful with this project.
  • rubber bands
  • long tape measure, roll wheel, or GPS and an app for measuring could get close enough in the right hands.
  • tape (if your wings are prone to fall off)
  • open space to launch (foot ball field, greenway, gym, use good judgement!)
  • calipers, rule, or tape to measure smaller things (if you are doing design-builds)
  • SAFETY GEAR
    • Assets
    I have included the body.f3d fusion 360 design files in the thing files. Modifications for other wing sizes or body designs could be made.
  • body.f3d
  • wing_test1.f3d
  • wing_test2.f3d
  • wing_test3.f3d
  • wing_test4.f3d

description.text:
Remix of the C/D-Bot Printers with the primary goal of going BIG: 600x600x500 (~24" x 24" x 20")

http://a360.co/2clcnSD
This is a new link that now works to download the file. Please, DO NOT print any of these parts yet. This is a work in progress posted for public review and feedback and I don't know if the parts as currently designed will work for you.

This is not a complete design. I am not going to tackle designing extruders, controller enclosures, etc. since there are so many great options already, including the designs by @cfeniak and @spauda01. (All mistakes, bad ideas and poor implementations are my own.)

  • The Fusion 360 model is fully parametric. If you don't like 600x600x500, go in and change the values and it will resize all the extrusions for you. This includes wheel parameters (radial and axial) and motor sizes.

  • 20x40mm V-Slot extrusions everywhere to enhance rigidity. Considering 20x60 for H-Beam and Y Rails.

  • Interchangeable hot-end mount. I designed for the Kraken, but could also see myself mounting a small diode laser, drag knife, or flexible shaft rotary tool.

  • Full size heated bed. I found a supplier who can make pretty much any size heater I need. Now I need to find a local source for borosilicate glass.

  • It's designed using OpenBuilds mini V-Wheels and eccentric spacers.

  • All parts have minimum wall thickness of 5mm. All parts have been updated to fully enclose the extrusion. Thanks to @spiffcow for the idea.

I want your feedback! See something I could do better? Tell me. Spot something that won't work? Please let me know!

• Capture the top of the lead screws. May consider rotating the bed 90 degrees and putting the lead screws front and back instead of on the sides.

  • I haven't finished the design of the bottom yet. Toying with ideas for feet on a table vs free standing. This big of a machine won't fit on a desk...

  • Would like to fully enclose it but the top parts will need some refinement first.

title: MagHak Virtual Reality Rifle (with magnetic quick connect)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a VR rifle designed to be used with the HTC Vive. This was based off an image posted on reddit hyping a commecial version being developed by u/Hooves_mcg. THIS IS A NON-COMMERCIAL PROJECT. It is intended to be open-source and community improved. THIS IS A WORK IN PROGRESS, and may not work as expected with individual setups.

This includes my ver. 1 printable stock (failed due to collision with Vive headset when using in-game scope) and my untested ver. 2 printable stock

Yeah, I just kind of threw it up there and my naming conventions can be confusing. OK, there are 4 main pieces to the body - they have the lower case letters (a,b,c,d) you will need 3x of the 'a' pieces (the rails) and 2x of each of the 'b','c', and 'd' pieces (which are the controller mounts). The 'b' piece has two variations - VVRb3 is the one i've been using the VVRb4 is an untested variation that I hope to try soon. SO, those get you the main body...

The stock: the 'e' piece is for adding your own aftermarket stock, but it also goes with the 'sA and sB' pieces for my first stock. The sA3, sB3, and sC3 are my untested stock to compensate for the headset when using the scope and don't require the 'e' piece to connect to the body.

Hope this helps.

In addition to the printed pieces the following will also be needed:

(8) 2.5# pull .3" x .11" (8mm x 3mm) cylindrical magnets http://www.homedepot.com/p/MASTER-MAGNETICS-0-3-in-x-0-11-in-Neodymium-Rare-Earth-Magnet-Discs-10-per-Pack-07045HD/202526363

(8) 1.25" #8-32 round head machine screws with #8-32 matching nuts.

super glue for the stock pieces and magnets.
